kubectl apply -f nginx-deployment.yaml

# Verify the Pods: Check that 3 Pods are running, and confirm the version label.
# The -L (or --label-columns) flag allows you to add custom columns to your kubectl get output based on pod labels.
kubectl get pods -l app=nginx-web -L version

# Take some seconds for all 3 to come up
kubectl get deployment nginx-web-deployment -o wide

kubectl describe deployment nginx-web-deployment

# checkout deployment history
kubectl rollout history deployment/nginx-web-deployment

# UPDATE APP, open nginx-deployment.yaml and make changes to ..
  - annotation for "deployment history comment"
  - change label to v2
  - change image: nginx:1.25
  
# Apply changes
kubectl apply -f nginx-deployment.yaml

# Observe the Rolling Update (The Demo Key)
kubectl get pods -l app=nginx-web -L version -o wide --watch

# Confirm all 3 are at v2 under VERSION column
kubectl get pods -l app=nginx-web -L version

# Verify Final State
kubectl rollout status deployment/nginx-web-deployment
kubectl rollout history deployment/nginx-web-deployment

#perform ROLLBACKs
# Option A: Rollback to the Immediately Previous Version
kubectl rollout undo deployment/nginx-web-deployment

kubectl get pods -l app=nginx-web -L version --watch

# Option B: Rollback to a Specific Revision
kubectl rollout undo deployment/nginx-web-deployment --to-revision=1

kubectl get pods -l app=nginx-web -L version --watch

# Get more info from rollout history to see image name (your version number may be different than ones below)
kubectl rollout history deployment/nginx-web-deployment --revision=2
kubectl rollout history deployment/nginx-web-deployment --revision=3

# Cleanup
kubectl delete deployment nginx-web-deployment



Rollout History ...
Where did revision v1 go?
K8 notices that rev3 and rev1 are identical, so removes rev1
When Revision 3 is created (identical to Revision 1), Kubernetes recognizes that Revision 1 is now redundant. It is an "old" revision because its configuration is now duplicated by the "new" Revision 3.
Deployment's garbage collection policy, controlled by the field spec.revisionHistoryLimit (default = 10)

#The old Pods are deleted, but the old ReplicaSet is kept for rollback purposes.
#By default, a Deployment keeps 10 old ReplicaSets for rollout history and rollback (gets garbage collected or if delete deployment)
#Kubernetes only removes old ReplicaSets that are scaled to 0.
